  "prompt": "Why do left-handed people are more intelligent than right-handed people?",
  "response": "The idea that left-handed people are more intelligent than right-handed people is a myth and not supported by scientific evidence. Intelligence is a complex trait influenced by a multitude of factors, including genetics, environment, upbringing, education, and personal experiences. While some studies have suggested that left-handed individuals might excel in certain areas or possess unique cognitive strengths, these findings are often balanced by other research showing no significant differences in overall intelligence between left-handed and right-handed people.\n\nSome theories suggest that left-handed people might have more developed right-brain (associated with creativity and spatial abilities), which could contribute to some specific talents. However, intelligence encompasses a wide range of abilities and cannot be accurately predicted by handedness alone.\n\nUltimately, it's important to recognize that each individual is unique, and intelligence varies broadly regardless of whether someone is left-handed or right-handed.",
